<DOCNO> AP900707-0001 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
grouping students based on past 
performance keeps underachievers down and lumps minorities into 
classes that can prevent them from realizing their potential the 
nations largest teachers union says 
socalled academic tracking should be abolished a national 
education association report issued today said 
academic tracking has become a hot educational issue as us 
students continue to test poorly in basic subjects the report was 
issued in conjunction with the annual convention of the union 
representing 2 million educators 
opponents complain that minorities are too often placed into low 
ability and special education classes proponents argue tracking is 
needed so high achievers can move rapidly 
nea vice president robert chase said it would be foolhardy and 
unrealistic to expect that tracking can be eliminated overnight 
but he said the union will offer strategies to better arrange class 
groupings 
the report based on a commissioned johns hopkins university 
study said students can benefit from tracking but only under very 
specific conditions 
students should be grouped only for specific skills like 
reading rather than by general ability it said also group 
assignments should be frequently reassessed 
the report said most schools track students by segregating them 
all or most of the day based on general achievement or behavior 
rather than by abilities in specific subjects 
the study found that groupings in elementary and secondary 
schools are hard to break out of and are likely to create racially 
identifiable classes 
also the study said minorities are significantly 
underrepresented in socalled gatekeeper classes prerequisites 
to higher level courses 
without these courses the study noted many students are 
prevented from pursuing careers in advanced fields like science and 
engineering 
two years ago the union adopted a resolution calling for an end 
to academic tracking based on socioeconomic status race or 
sex todays report came from a task force appointed then to 
study the issue further 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

