<DOCNO> AP900707-0005 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bearing the offer of a nonaggression pact and a 
pledge to cut german forces nato secretary general manfred woerner 
is heading for moscow on the alliances most hopeful mission yet 
for allaying soviet fears about german unification and decades of 
eastwest enmity 
a day after woerner arrives in the soviet capital on july 14 
west german chancellor helmut kohl will also meet with president 
mikhail s gorbachev 
the visits reflect a steppedup drive by the western allies to 
develop new ties and pacts with the soviet union following natos 
dramatic revamping of its longstanding military strategy at a 
summit which ended friday in london 
the london declaration transforms our relationship with old 
adversaries declared president bush who drafted the new 
doctrine to those governments who confronted us in the cold war 
our alliance extends the hand of friendship 
in a communique the 16 nato leaders pledged to reduce sharply 
both nuclear and conventional defenses in europe and said they held 
no aggressive intentions toward the soviet union they promised 
they will never in any circumstance be the first to use force 
in moscow gorbachev said he was ready to accept an invitation 
from the london summit to address a nato meeting probably in 
december 
soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze welcomed the 
summits outcome saying the decisions move in the right 
direction and pave the way to a safe future for the entire european 
continent 
bush headed for houston aboard air force one when informed of 
shevardnadzes comments replied thats very interesting and 
very positive 
but it remained unclear whether the alliances solemn pledges 
would be enough to persuade gorbachev to drop his objections to a 
united germany being a member of nato 
i would like to see the tangible response be an acceptance of 
the concept that a unified germany in nato is not only good but 
that it certainly is no threat to them said bush 
kohl called the commitment to cut german troop levels an 
indispensable signpost along the path leading to german unity 
this is a wideranging offer said kohl of natos new 
stance this is nato offering a hand 
the nato leaders committed themselves to decide on a troop level 
for a unified germany by the autumn 
the new reduced level will then become part of the next round of 
negotiations with the soviets on lower overall troop levels for 
both nato and the warsaw pact 
bonns defense minister gerhard stoltenberg has agreed to cut 
more than 160000 from the current combined forces of west and east 
germany down to 400000 foreign minister hansdietrich genscher 
has said an even greater cut to 350000 troops is acceptable 
at the summit the allies also agreed to the eventual 
elimination of all nuclear artillery shells in europe in return for 
reciprocal action from the soviet union and they decided to 
field smaller and restructured ground forces 
in a switch in strategy that upset france and had made britain 
uneasy the nato leaders relegated nuclear weapons to being weapons 
of last resort 
french president francois mitterrand objected saying nato 
should stick to its longtime doctrine that it might use nuclear 
weapons to repel an overwhelming soviet conventional attack 
british prime minister margaret thatcher came round to the 
concept after insisting that the communique stress nato retains the 
option of using nuclear weapons she also said last resort was 
sufficient now that the crumbling warsaw pact has lost the ability 
to mount a surprise attack 
at long last we have the chance to make for the first time in 
history military aggression in europe materially impossible and 
also politically meaningless declared woerner 
</TEXT>
