<TEXT>
critical tests to ferret out the mysterious 
hydrogen leak that has grounded americas space shuttle fleet are 
starting this weekend 
rockwell international the contractor that built the space 
shuttles will test pipes and valves from space shuttle columbia 
today and sunday at the company plant in downey calif 
engineers at the kennedy space center in florida meanwhile are 
preparing a leak test on atlantis a space shuttle on a launch pad 
william lenoir nasa associate administrator for space flight 
said friday the goal of the tests is to find where a leak developed 
in the maze of pipes and valves used to load liquid hydrogen aboard 
the shuttles 
leaks found in may on columbia and last week on atlantis caused 
the national aeronautics and space administration to ground all 
three of the nations winged spacecraft the third craft 
discovery is scheduled to fly in october if the leak problem is 
solved 
meanwhile friday an investigative board concluded two days of 
closeddoor hearings here on another major nasa problem the 
focusing flaw that disabled the 15 billion hubble space telescope 
nasa said the panel led by lew allen director of the space 
agencys jet propulsion laboratory was to determine how a 
manufacturer ground and polished the wrong prescription into one of 
two focusing mirrors on the telescope the mistake has caused the 
instrument to see the universe as a fuzzy blur 
the mirrors were manufactured by the hughes danbury optical co 
of danbury conn under a 440 million contract that included 11 
million in performance awards 
a report to be published monday in aviation week and space 
technology magazine quotes unnamed sources as saying nasa was 
offered air force facilities to test the telescope mirrors 10 years 
ago but the space agency turned down the offer 
but another trade publication space business news says in a 
story to be published monday that nasa was blocked from using 
defense department facilities to test the hubble mirrors because 
the same contractor also was making optics for air force spy 
satellites 
space business news quotes james beggs who was nasa 
administrator when the hubble was being built as saying that the 
air force wouldnt let us in to test the hubble mirrors or to 
even oversee their manufacture 
efforts to reach beggs by telephone for comment were 
unsuccessful 
lenoir told reporters there is still no estimate about how long 
the space shuttles will be grounded it all depends on how long it 
takes to find and fix the hydrogen leaks he said 
a leak discovered on atlantis during a test on the launch pad 
last week is similar to one discovered in may on columbia when that 
craft was being loaded with liquid hydrogen in preparation for 
launch 
columbia was rolled back to the hangar and engineers removed the 
elaborate plumbing fixture called the umbilical that is used to 
load hydrogen into the shuttle rocket propellant tank the fixture 
was sent to the rockwell plant in downey for testing 
on sunday rockwell engineers plan to pump helium then liquid 
nitrogen and finally the much colder liquid hydrogen through the 
umbilical 
if it does leak we should be able to pinpoint it lenoir 
said 
a more vigorous test is planned for atlantis next friday when 
liquid hydrogen is pumped into the spacecrafts tank at a high rate 
of flow plastic bags will be placed over the various valves pipes 
and seals that are suspected of leaking gas captured in the bags 
will be analyzed to determine the hydrogen content lenoir said 
if we get through all of that and we still cant find a leak 
then in all honesty we dont know where well go he said 
engineers earlier suspected that the leaks may have been caused 
by a slightly crooked installation of propellant tanks on both 
atlantis and columbia but lenoir said an analysis of the 
misalignment determined it could not be responsible for the leak 
at rockwell internationals assembly plant in palmdale calif 
meanwhile power surged friday for the first time into endeavour 
the newest member of americas space shuttle fleet 
a nasa announcement called the powerup a major milestone in 
testing of the new shuttles electrical system the spacecraft is 
scheduled to be completed in april 1991 and make its first flight 
in 1992 
