<TEXT>
to f scott fitzgerald they were 
breathlessly aristocratic clubs frequented by an impressive 
melange of brilliant adventurers and welldressed philanderers 
to sally frank princeton universitys menonly eating clubs are 
part of an oldboy network that discriminates against women 
fitzgerald venerated the tiger inn and the ivy and cottage clubs 
in the 1920 novel this side of paradise almost 60 years later 
ms frank sued the three organizations seeking membership in the 
ivy league schools menonly clubs 
after an 11year battle during which she was vilified by other 
students ms frank a 1980 princeton graduate prevailed last week 
when the new jersey supreme court ordered the clubs to open their 
doors to the opposite sex 
ms frank now a 31yearold law professor at the new york 
university law school said she fought for so long because she 
believed the battle had implications beyond the gothicstyle 
ivyshrouded campus 
you always have clubs that call themselves private across the 
nation where major business and political leaders are members and 
people take tax deductions for their members ms frank said 
we know that important business contacts are made in those 
places and public policy decisions are often made over the dinner 
table she said the case is part of the broader struggle to 
stop discrimination in those kinds of organizations 
the centuryold eating clubs which are near campus serve meals 
to more than 75 percent of princetons juniors and seniors they do 
not provide living quarters the clubs have competitive standards 
for admission and students pay membership fees 
the cachet of the clubs made a deep impression on princeton 
alumnus fitzgerald who described the ivy club as detached and 
breathlessly aristocratic in his romantic vision the university 
cottage club attracted brilliant adventurers and welldressed 
philanderers while the tiger inn preferred the 
broadshouldered and athletic type 
such distinctions did not sit well with ms frank who was 
raised in bayonne and said her sense of social justice grew out of 
the chicago eight trial and the kent state shootings at 12 she 
boycotted nonunion lettuce and at age 13 she worked for 
presidential candidate george mcgovern 
she said she had no inkling that her attempt to join menonly 
clubs in an institution that first accepted women in 1969 would 
spark such a ruckus 
i thought that they would be intelligent about it and that 
they would see it as an issue and argue or debate it ms frank 
said i expected some hot repartee 
instead a club member poured beer on her she was booed at 
alumni rallies and her face was painted with a mustache on 
frankbuster tshirts that said better dead than coed 
things have changed at princeton since the lawsuit was filed in 
1979 
the cottage club settled in 1986 and now accepts women the ivy 
club and the tiger inn the only two of the 13 eating clubs to 
cling to maleonly membership had voted earlier this year to admit 
women but two more rounds of voting were needed next year for the 
decision to become effective 
in court the tiger inn and ivy club had argued they were 
private associations and therefore exempt from state 
antidiscrimination laws but the supreme court said it was 
disingenuous for the clubs to pretend they could exist apart 
from the school the clubs the court said are places of public 
accommodation 
the tiger inn president has promised to take the case to the 
us supreme court 
princetons clubs are the first at an ivy league school to be 
ordered to admit women the massachusetts commission against 
discrimination ruled in march that it had no jurisdiction to decide 
the case of a woman seeking admission to the fly club one of 
harvards nine allmale social clubs yales most exclusive secret 
society skull amp bones of which george bush is a member recently 
voted to continue excluding women 
in a gauge of how far princeton has come the alumni council 
last month gave ms frank an award for her efforts in encouraging 
coeducation 
it felt really warm and nice she said what the award 
meant to me was that just because you are a dissenter it doesnt 
mean you are not loyal 
