for disease control says 
nearly 13 percent of the 22411 fatal injuries to children in 
1986 were homicides second only to motor vehicle accidents the 
agency said friday it said 1986 is the latest year for which 
complete statistics are available 
auto accidents accounted for 10535 deaths in people under 20 in 
1986 and between 15 percent and 30 percent of those deaths were 
associated with alcohol researchers said 
the agency said 2877 people under age 20 died from homicide in 
1986 and 660 of them or 23 percent were under 5 
suicide was the third leading cause of childhood fatal injuries 
accounting for 2151 deaths in 1986 males accounted for 80 
percent and the suicide rate was roughly twice as high for whites 
as for blacks 
drowning the fourth leading cause of childhood fatal injuries 
killed 2062 youths it was the most common fatal injury among kids 
under 5 and among young men 1519 
death rates for children from causes other than injuries dropped 
by 56 percent between 1968 and 1986 deaths from injuries fell 22 
percent in the same period the agency said 
in 1986 a total of 71383 people under 20 died in this country 
