<TEXT>
americans living abroad say the us government 
isnt doing enough to help them solve problems involving taxes 
voting education and citizenship 
the us expatriates concluded their first world conference 
friday by urging the government not to ignore them just because 
they dont live in the united states 
john f crawford the meetings cochairman said the twoday 
gathering could eventually lead to an expatriates bill of 
rights 
he argued that creating better conditions for the estimated 3 
million us citizens abroad could help american competitiveness in 
world markets 
the 200 expatriates who came from as far away as brazil and 
nigeria for the paris gathering said the united states lags behind 
other nations in helping its citizens overseas 
for example the united states is the only industrial nation 
that taxes citizen overseas on income earned abroad it allows 
expatriates no representation in congress unlike france for one 
whose overseas citizens have six senate representatives 
overseas americans can have problems ensuring citizenship for 
their children and their schools unlike those for japanese 
germans and french living abroad receive no government help 
the expatriates are also denied medicare and medicaid even 
though they make social security payments 
the group said its goals included congressional representation 
a congressional task force to deal with their problems and a 
highlevel panel made up of representatives of various government 
agencies to handle expatriate concerns 
other ideas discussed at the conference included teacher 
exchange programs bringing innercity american children to foreign 
american schools to widen their horizons and getting more overseas 
americans to participate in us elections 
rep mervyn m dymally rcalif said he already was taking 
steps to set up a congressional task force dymally who was one of 
10 members of congress at the paris meeting presided over hearings 
last november on overseas americans he said more hearings were 
planned this fall 
ben blaz who represents the pacific territory of guam in 
congress said overseas americans would have to work to win the 
attention of washington or their needs would continue to be ignored 
the burden is on you to change that attitude he said 
the meeting was sponsored by the association of americans 
resident overseas the european council of american chambers of 
commerce american citizens abroad democrats abroad federation of 
american womens clubs overseas and republicans abroad 
