<TEXT>
a band of rogue bell ringers has been pealing 
under false pretenses in lincolnshire and vicars throughout 
england will be on the alert sunday for rats in their belfries 
six to eight bogus ringers have recently rung unsafe bells at 
four churches in the diocese of lincoln endangering themselves 
others and the bells according to church of england officials 
the rogues struck at st clements in worlaby and st andrews 
in bonby on the south bank of the humber and at two other 
churches that have not been identified similar incidents were 
reported in cambridgeshire earlier this year and a bell tower in a 
village church was damaged 
robin heppenstall secretary of the lincoln diocese guild of 
church bellringers said the pealers duped vicars and church 
wardens into allowing them into the towers where they rang bells 
long silent because of their dangerous condition 
it is conceivable that the clapper inside the bell could be 
worn and faulty and if it flies out it could go anywhere 
heppenstall said 
if that went out through a window it could conceivably injure 
someone seriously he warned 
it could be churches were thinking of spending a few hundred 
pounds to make the bell tower safe and the bells operational and 
then suddenly they are faced with a bigger bill he said 
the bells anchored on frames and weighing about 1000 pounds 
revolve 360 degrees 
if the frame is badly worn or eaten by woodworm and you start 
ringing there is considerable force the whole frame could collapse 
under the energy of the bell he said 
bell ringers require months of training heppenstall said 
ive seen people lifted several feet into the air because 
theyve lost control of the bell he said these tower grabbers 
are competent people they appear to have some knowledge of bell 
ringing 
each of the 5425 belfries in england provides a unique 
experience for ringers the size the weight the casting and the 
way the bell is hung contribute to a distinctive toll and feel 
they sound differently and you can go on a little outing and 
