<TEXT>
world leaders will focus on global warming and 
the destruction of rain forests at the economic summit but they 
are unlikely to do enough to satisfy environmentalists 
president bush and his six summit partners are expected to sign 
a communique outlining how they will cooperate on international 
environmental issues 
several environmental groups who will be on hand with an 
environmental scorecard to grade the summit are skeptical 
about what the leaders of the industrial nations will accomplish 
the people of the world want more than just communiques that 
sound environmental they want policies that are environmentally 
sound said fred krupp executive director of the environmental 
defense fund 
global warming the socalled greenhouse effect has emerged 
as a thorny international environmental issue scientists say 
gaseous emissions trap solar heat causing a gradual warming of the 
earth 
while several european nations already have plans to reduce or 
stabilize carbon dioxide emissions by the year 2000 of 2005 bush 
contends more research is needed on global warming before such 
dramatic steps need be taken 
in advance of the summit us officials said participants are 
expected to agree on the outlines of an international convention 
to be held by 1992 to discuss global warming 
but the officials speaking on condition they remain anonymous 
said they appear to have avoided what could have been a bruising 
battle at the summit with european nations over the reduction of 
gaseous emissions 
the officials said the europeans seem to be willing to back away 
from their previous insistence that specific reduction goals be set 
at the summit led by germany some countries had sought a 
commitment to stabilize carbon dioxide emissions or reduce them by 
up to 25 percent by the end of the decade 
there is still wrangling however over when the nations should 
begin work on agreements to formally spell out how they will fight 
global warming administration officials said 
two other contentious areas involve curtailing the destruction 
of tropical forests and setting up an international green fund 
to help developing countries protect their environments 
the united states is not anxious to sign any agreements curbing 
the destruction of tropical forests but one official said im 
not going to throw down my body in front of a train if others 
nations devise a plan 
the summiteers are expected to agree on strengthening the 
tropical forestry action plan that was conceived in the mid1980s 
by the world bank and other international organizations 
the plan channels international investment into tropical 
countries to help them develop land use policies that will help 
save forests 
the plans critics say so far the projects selected to receive 
money ignore forestry protection goals there is a general feeling 
among the summit partners that a tougher plan is needed one us 
official said 
meantime the world bank is viewed as the most likely vehicle to 
administer a green fund to provide money for developing 
nations environmental projects 
but the bush administration will oppose a separately financed 
green fund at the world bank which lends money to poor 
countries for various projects one administration official said 
the united states would probably go along with a green fund if 
it were paid for out of existing resources a position some 
europeans would oppose 
bush in an attempt to blunt any criticism of the united states 
as reticent on global warming or other issues intends to tell his 
summit partners at tuesdays environmental session about recent 
us environmental accomplishments 
officials say he will recite a series of steps that when 
combined according to administration projections would stabilize 
or even reduce carbon dioxide emissions by the end of the decade 
they include the clean air act still pending in congress 
bushs plan to plant 1 billion trees a year and purchase wilderness 
areas and the us commitment to the elimination of 
ozonedepleting chemicals by the year 2000 
the economic summit communique is likely to include endorsement 
of the recent 93nation agreement in london to wipe out 
chlorofluorocarbons chemicals that deplete the earths protective 
ozone layer by the end of the decade 
