<TEXT>
the nations largest teachers union 
issued a report saturday calling for a gradual end to the 
controversial practice of grouping students according to past 
performance 
robert chase vice president of the national education 
association said it would be foolhardy and unrealistic to expect 
that tracking can be eliminated overnight but said the union 
will offer strategies to better arrange class groupings 
academic tracking has become a hot educational issue as us 
students continue to test poorly in basic subjects opponents 
complain that minorities are too often placed into low ability and 
special education classes proponents argue tracking is needed so 
high achievers can move rapidly 
we must give students an education that will open up their 
options for the future not close them said chase at a news 
conference at the annual convention of the union representing 2 
million educators 
chase pointed to a carnegie study issued two years ago that 
found 63 percent of all us teachers considered tracking useful 
the report based on a commissioned johns hopkins university 
study said students can benefit from tracking but only under very 
specific conditions 
sue hovey of moscow idaho who worked on the nea report said 
students should be grouped only for specific skills like reading 
rather than by general ability also group assignments should be 
frequently reassessed 
the report said most schools track students by segregating them 
all or most of the day according to general achievement or 
behavior rather than by abilities in specific subjects 
the study found that groupings in elementary and secondary 
schools are hard to break out of and are likely to create racially 
identifiable classes 
leon horne an nea executive committee member who chaired the 
task force handling the report said the study also found that 
minorities are significantly underrepresented in classes that are 
prerequisites to higher level courses 
without these courses horne said many students are prevented 
from pursuing careers in advanced fields like science and 
engineering 
two years ago the union proposed and debated a resolution 
calling for an end to academic tracking based on socioeconomic 
status race or sex saturdays report came from a task force 
appointed then to study the issue further 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

