tens of thousands of african 
national congress supporters marched in cities across the country 
saturday to protest black factional fighting in natal province that 
has claimed thousands of lives 
official permission was granted for about 20 peace marches 
planned by the anc and its allies the congress of south african 
trade unions and the united democratic front to mark the end of a 
week of national protest against the violence petitions protesting 
the violence were presented to authorities at various police 
stations throughout the country 
about 80000 protesters staged a peaceful march through the 
streets in the eastern cape province city of port elizabeth the 
high turnout was attributed to the region being a traditional anc 
stronghold 
there were no incidents despite a heavy police and army presence 
and the sealing off of some roads with barbed wire 
the march was led by recently returned anc exile thobile mhlahlo 
and former police lieutenant gregory rockman who last year exposed 
incidents of police brutality 
a memorandum delivered to police read this is not 
blackonblack violence its also neither faction fighting but 
apartheid war president fw de klerk was urged to stop the 
violence 
about 12000 people marched through the natal capital durban 
protesters carried huge cloth banners that read stop the 
apartheid war defend natal 
they presented a memo to the local police commander col kobus 
le roux 
