<TEXT>
mikhail s gorbachev turned defeat into victory 
saturday by persuading the communist party congress to drop plans 
to evaluate each member of the ruling politburo warning that such 
action would bury the party 
delegates to the 28th communist party congress have criticized 
many of the 12 politburo members and wanted to give the thumbsup 
or thumbsdown on each of them 
the delegates voted 2557 to 1393 for such a chance before 
their afternoon break but gorbachev later warned if you want to 
bury the party to split the party then continue on this way 
think think hard think hard 
the ire of the 59yearold soviet leader who has skillfully 
consolidated his position at the congress prompted the delegates 
to vote 2495 to 1515 to reverse themselves 
in his argument gorbachev read a note from the northern russian 
city of arkhangelsk that said there is no need to evaluate each 
politburo member the politburo according to the rules is an 
organ of the leadership and the leadership is collective 
instead the congress agreed to evaluate the policymaking 
central committee and within it the politburo as a whole 
politburo member vladimir ivashko later read a draft of a 
resolution on the central committee that is to be voted on this 
week 
the draft praises the committee for major changes enacted since 
the last congress in 1986 the move toward democracy and free 
elections but it blames the party for failing to carry out party 
policy leading to social and economic difficulties 
the congress broke a decadesold tradition last week by 
requiring each politburo member to account for his work and answer 
written questions from the nearly 4700 delegates 
inna dementyeva a moscow delegate said the vote on personal 
evaluations would have gone too far 
our russian thirst for blood is showing she said its 
stupid and ugly and inhuman 
delegates interviewed in the lobby of the kremlin palace of 
congresses said that allowing the mostly conservative congress to 
vote on individual leaders also might have embarrassed gorbachev 
and his allies and benefited such conservative critics as yegor k 
ligachev 
some also said they had expected at least half the politburo to 
get the thumbs down particulary ideology chief vadim a medvedev 
and international policy head alexander n yakovlev 
collective responsibility is no responsibility said a 
byelorussian delegate who identified himself only as alexander 
and there should be a full renewal of the leadership 
several politburo members responded to the written questions 
they received from delegates and medvedev said he had been accused 
of letting party ideology crumble and discipline among soviet 
journalists break down 
he responded that the party had shed fossilized thinking and 
dogmatism and that journalists should be governed by law and 
their party and civic conscience 
yakovlev one of gorbachevs closest advisers said he had been 
accused of connivance to separatism in the baltic republics and 
the loss of eastern europe 
he responded that he had spoken out against separatism and 
nationalism and that the people of eastern europe were the ones who 
rejected the communist party 
ligachev also took the floor and said he opposed reunification 
of the german states because the west was absorbing the east 
he criticized the concept of private property and plans to 
convert the soviet union to a marketoriented economy saying 
proponents of free market relations should become the first 
soviet unemployed 
ligachev also opposed political reforms that would diminish the 
partys role in society and government i dont see another force 
other than the party which could bring progress to our country 
he said 
foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze defended soviet policy 
on german unity saying moscows interests could best be served 
through international negotiations rather than attempts to block 
the merger 
he received only mild applause but drew strong support when he 
reminded the congress that the republic of georgia under his 
leadership started to fight corruption in the party 
although gorbachev preserved the facade of collective leadership 
by defeating individual evaluations of politburo members major 
personnel changes are expected at the congress yakovlev medvedev 
and lev zaikov have indicated they plan to step down from the 
politburo 
the congress will choose a new central committee which in turn 
will select a new politburo 
delegates said there did not appear to be any serious challenge 
to gorbachev as party leader nominations for the post were delayed 
until later this week 
in a draft of party rules the congress will elect a new party 
leader the general secretary and create a new post of deputy 
general secretary also to be elected by the congress 
among the candidates mentioned for the no 2 post are ligachev 
premier nikolai i ryzhkov interior minister vadim bakatin and 
pravda editor ivan frolov but gorbachev adviser georgy 
shakhnazarov said he thought the deputy might turn out to be 
someone completely new 
