police here have been authorized to 
use stun guns as an alternative to nightsticks but theres a catch 
any officer who wants to use the device has to get zapped first 
to know what its like 
forty pompano beach officers have signed up for a sixhour 
course on the use of the electric weapon the officers are 
responsible for buying their own stun guns which cost an average 
of about 150 
getting zapped is the last part of the course and on friday 
officers of all sizes yelled and crumpled helplessly to the ground 
when they were touched with the stun gun and the electricity hit 
their muscles 
its really a convincer officer bill butler said after he 
experienced it its like something really biting into you 
it hurt a lot said officer kathy konieczka 
after being zapped officers said they would not hesitate to use 
the guns as a last resort in place of physical restraint 
a nightstick will injure someone butler said 
officer ken holland who is in charge of the training program 
said the stun guns are completely safe but there are precautions 
an officer must stop the current as soon as the subject falls and 
they are forbidden to place the device on a persons head face or 
groin 
twelve officers carried the guns during a pilot program that 
began in february the weapons have been used 12 times with no 
complaints and no injuries holland said 
all were violent or potentially violent situations he said 
we had no allegations of abuse or use of excessive force 
the weapons shock is supposed to do nothing more than render a 
person defenseless for a few seconds 
it has nothing to do with your brain or heart police 
spokeswoman sandra king said your muscles will go limp for a 
couple of seconds 
and use of the guns will be strictly monitored 
any time the officer takes it out or shows it to someone they 
have to fill out a long form explaining why they pulled it out 
king said 
