yugoslavias republic of serbia 
tightened its grip on the ethnic albanian majority in kosovo 
province saturday by disbanding the official trade union 
organization there 
the yugoslav news agency tanjug said the council of trade unions 
of serbia acted because the kosovo council failed to perform its 
role 
in pristina capital of kosovo the albanianlanguage daily 
rilindija carried a sharp protest of serbias occupation of 
kosovo 
ethnic albanians dominate the province and their leaders issued 
a declaration of independence last monday 
serbia responded thursday by dissolving kosovos local governing 
bodies replacing the managers and leading journalists of local 
news organizations and taking albanianlanguage radio and 
television programs off the air 
on friday serbian authorities detained several ethnic albanians 
and large numbers of uniformed police took up positions throughout 
pristina kosovos capital about 150 miles south of belgrade 
heightened security also was reported from other towns in the 
province 
kosovo was calm on saturday tanjug reported 
a group of provincial deputies demanded an emergency session of 
the federal legislature to discuss the situation 
serbian authorities dissolved the local assembly and government 
after 114 assembly members announced plans to secede from serbia 
the largest of the countrys six republics both bodies were 
dominated by ethnic albanians who make up 90 percent of the 
provinces 19 million people 
serbias moves have virtually abolished the autonomy granted the 
southern province under the 1974 yugoslav constitution 
at least 60 ethnic albanians have died in clashes with security 
forces since serbia began limiting autonomy in march 1989 
serbians consider kosovo the cradle of their medieval kingdom 
they allege ethnic albanians in seeking independence have 
pressured serbians to move out 
ethnic albanians who want free elections and a multiparty 
system deny serbias charges 
they say serbias communist leader slobodan milosevic has used 
such accusations to gain popular support for his drive to control 
kosovo 
the trouble in kosovo is one of many besetting yugoslavias 
fragile communistrun federal governement 
the northern republic of slovenia on monday adopted a 
declaration of regional autonomy and said it would take control of 
yugoslav military on its soil 
yugoslavias federal leadership on friday demanded that the 
republic rescind its proclamation but slovenias presidency on 
saturday refused the tanjug news agency reported 
the authority of the federal leadership has effectively been 
crippled since noncommunist centerright parties won elections 
this year in slovenia and croatia another liberal republic it was 
the first free balloting in yugoslavia in 50 years 
slovenia and croatia are demanding a looser national 
confederation 
the current federation of six republics and two autonomous 
provinces already allows each region to run its own government and 
communist party structure 
the decentralized system of government was devised by the late 
national leader josip broz tito it was intended to prevent one 
republic from gaining sway over the others but ethnic and economic 
differences are again threatening the countrys unity 
