<TEXT>
the worlds poorest nations have told the 
industrial countries meeting at a houston summit that they must 
provide more aid and debt relief to avoid a spiral of poverty and 
social unrest in the third world 
it is proved beyond a shadow of a doubt that there is no 
substitute for a market economy and this is what we strive to 
achieve said ahg mohiuddin un ambassador of bangladesh and 
spokesman for the 42 nations known as the least developed countries 
but if our efforts are not met by commensurate aid we will be 
faced with social unrest which will undo all our good work he 
said in an interview before this weeks houston summit of the 
united states and six other leading industrial nations 
we have tightened our belts beyond our capacity and if there 
is a failure in reciprocal commitment from the industrial world 
then it will be suicidal for us he said 
mohiuddin has visited the capitals of the seven nations to 
sensitize them to the needs of the impoverished third world 
the poorest of the poor 
the poor nations are calling for development assistance in the 
form of 15 percent of the industrial nations gross national 
product by 1995 and 20 percent by the end of the decade they also 
seek debt cancellation and reduction and removal of trade barriers 
to their exports 
in general the bangladesh envoy said the response was positive 
but not specific the poorest nations hope that the final 
communique from the houston summit will address some of their 
problems 
nordic countries and most participants in the houston summit are 
approaching or have reached the development assistance sought by 
the poor nations 
however the united states and japan which give extensive aid 
have opposed aid targets the united states gives about 04 percent 
of its gnp the total annual value of produced goods and services 
to the worlds poorest nations 
the houston session could foreshadow what will happen at an 
international conference on the least developed countries in paris 
in september when a plan of domestic action and foreign help is to 
be developed officials of the poorest nations hope the wealthiest 
ones will persuade others in the international arena to support 
their cause 
but the wealthiest nations recently have been emphasizing the 
importance of respecting human rights and instituting democratic 
political reforms as conditions for foreign aid in eastern europe 
and elsewhere 
the poorest nations respond by saying that poverty is the 
greatest obstacle to human rights everywhere 
the poorest nations have expressed concern that aid to the 
emerging democracies of eastern europe should not take away from 
the industrial nations commitment to help the poorest countries 
which have a total of 475 million people 
the least developed countries as defined by the world bank are 
the worlds most abjectly poor with average per capita incomes of 
less than 500 per year 
their total foreign debt is about 55 billion their annual debt 
service payment alone is nearly 4 billion 
