more than 170 wildfires still raged 
across alaska on saturday and fire officials expressed concern the 
blazes could threaten small towns for weeks 
hot dry weather in tandem with thousands of firecausing 
lightning strikes is making the summer fire season much worse 
than years past said pete buist a spokesman for an interagency 
fire information center at fairbanks 
in a more typical summer tundra and forests would be wetter 
humidity higher and most fires would be monitored but not 
aggressively fought he said but under the weather conditions we 
have now we start manning fires that we would not ordinarily 
unlike other western states where policies to let fires burn 
have been criticized alaska fire managers typically allow most 
wildfires to burn because they seldom pose a risk to people or 
property 
no lives or homes have been lost to alaska fires this year 
authorities said but massive fires across the state are burning 
nearer to villages than usual 
throughout alaska some 2400 firefighters were battling fires 
consuming more than 280225 acres in a wide eastwest band across 
the flat tundra and black spruce forests of the sparsely populated 
interior 
