<TEXT>
from the sugar fields of cuba to the shores of 
the kurile islands the ghost of josef stalin is haunting mikhail 
gorbachevs effort to win economic aid from the west 
with gorbachevs survival at stake western nations are flirting 
with a 15 billion economic aid package to moscow an issue that 
is likely to dominate the economic summit of industrialized nations 
that begins here on monday 
bush received a recent message from gorbachev and it was learned 
saturday that the soviet leader made his case for us assistance 
it was virtually the same request that gorbachev conveyed within 
the last two weeks to leaders of west germany and france 
west germany france and italy are eager to proceed but 
gorbachev may have to reverse decadesold soviet policy before the 
united states and japan will go along no one is expecting a 
consensus from this summit 
the sticking points for the united states soviet assistance to 
cuba and modernization of the red army 
for japan four kurile islands seized by stalin after world war 
ii 
after ridiculing the notion earlier in the year president bush 
seems to be slowly setting the stage for direct american aid to 
moscow but it isnt going to happen now he indicated on friday 
i have some big problems with that one and i think the 
american people do too president bush told reporters after the 
nato summit in london he said commercial trade credits might be 
possible but that the united states will not provide direct aid so 
long as the soviet union sends 5 billion a year to prop up the 
cuban economy 
perhaps more importantly bush also urged gorbachev to scale 
back the percentage of soviet spending devoted to the military 
secretary of state james a baker iii says moscow has been spending 
between 18 and 25 percent of its economy on military expansion 
which in the past has been hostile to the united states 
baker also said we really ought to see some progress toward 
economic reforms before sending american taxpayer funds to 
moscow we ought to have some faith that the money will be well 
spent he told cnn 
one obstacle dates back past stalin to the czarist days it is a 
legal restriction on credit to the soviet union based on 
prerevolutionary debt of several hundred million dollars 
on cuba bush is stating an american political reality the 
united states isnt going to subsidize moscow so that moscow can 
subsidize cuba 
soviet economic aid to cuba is estimated by us officials at 
more than 4 billion a year mostly in the form of subsidies for 
cuban exports such as sugar cuba receives an additional 15 
billion in military aid according to us figures 
aidtocuba is already the subject of heated debate in moscow 
where some argue that it would be wrong to turn on an ally under 
threat from the united states others say the kremlin cannot 
justify a largescale aid program at a time of economic decline at 
home 
japan is joining bush in using the economic aid question as a 
wedge to reverse longheld soviet policies the japanese are 
keeping their prodigious wallets zipped pending the outcome of a 
peace treaty that involves the kurile chain of islands 
in an interview shortly before leaving for houston japanese 
prime minister toshiki kaifu said it was soviet expansionism at 
the end of world war ii that prompted stalin to seize four of the 
kurile islands from japan 
he told the new york times that economic aid to gorbachev will 
not be possible until the northern territories conflict is 
resolved despite warming relations between japan and the soviet 
union a resolution will be none too simple since the islands 
etorofu kunashira shikotan and habomai are not the only or even 
the most prominent territories seized by stalin 
while japan is playing hardball on aid to moscow kaifu also is 
carrying the torch for resumption of western aid to china its 
possible japan will lift its sanctions against china even if the 
other summit nations do not bush allowed as much on saturday 
saying sometimes there are interests that predominate 
japan sees china as a huge and natural market and is anxious to 
proceed with a 5 billion aid package 
west germanys effort to win aid for moscow also seems to have a 
selfserving edge 
the communist party daily pravda said in a recent commentary 
that bonn was trying to grease the way for soviet approval of 
the key tenets of german unification 
despite his best efforts west german chancellor helmut kohl 
says the issue may not come to a head until the end of the year 
we are not under time pressure he told reporters in london 
on friday 
not under time pressure gorbachev said last week that if the 
soviet economy isnt awakening within two years hell give way 
with the ghost of stalin still complicating international affairs 
no one in the west is eager for that to happen 
