western leaders gathering for backtoback 
summits shifted continents saturday to take up a series of tough 
economic issues and mull the encouraging reaction from moscow to 
changes in the nato military alliance 
president bush welcomed his guests in the sweltering heat of his 
adopted hometown and met over a presummit lunch with toshiki 
kaifu the prime minister of japan 
their discussions touched on several of the most difficult 
issues that would arise monday when the formal summit meetings 
begin aid to moscow loans to china and trade among the allies 
themselves bush hinted that he wouldnt try to block kaifus 
intention to resume economic aid to china 
the prospering allies were trying to map a coordinated strategy 
to deal with the breakup of the communist bloc the 16th annual 
economic summit meeting is the first held in america since a 
gathering in williamsburg va in 1983 
a decision on sending aid to moscow was not expected to emerge 
this week but the climate was growing more hospitable and bushs 
spokesman marlin fitzwater said of the summit leaders there 
are a lot of things they can consider short of direct aid 
bush told kaifu according to fitzwater that he was very 
pleased with the reaction of the soviet union to the nato summit 
we have read the reports of comments by president gorbachev as well 
as foreign minister eduard shevardnadze and we are very pleased 
