alluded to the legislation approved earlier this month in albany 
the bill allows the sick to appoint proxies to make healthcare 
decisions for them when they are no longer able to do so the 
ruling opens the possibility of a proxy deciding that an 
incapacitated person should be allowed to die 
the legislation was passed after the us supreme court ruled 
that a missouri woman in an irreversible coma could not be 
disconnected from lifesupport equipment because it was unclear 
what her wishes would have been 
new york gov mario cuomo a roman catholic has not yet signed 
the bill into law but is expected to do so 
abortion and euthanasia express the same idea that human life 
belongs exclusively to man and that everyone is the exclusive owner 
of his life the editorial said 
the newspaper said only god had the right to terminate life 
if even the people who are asked to wisely govern the human 
community have fallen into such blackness as to promulgate such 
antihuman laws the culture and mentality of the end of the 
century have lost their sense of authentic values the editorial 
said 
in a lastminute concession aimed at avoiding the active 
opposition of new york states roman catholic bishops legislators 
said private hospitals could refuse for moral or religious 
reasons to carry out a proxy order to end life support 
the hospital would however have to inform the patient upon 
admission that it would not honor a proxys decision 
