<TEXT>
a slow economy pressing debts and fewer readers 
have combined to demonstrate vividly the growing vulnerability 
among american newspaper publishers 
two of the most prominent names in newspapering ralph m 
ingersoll ii and the gannett co emerged this past week as the 
latest sufferers from a slowdown in what historically has been a 
highly profitable industry 
ingersoll the ambitious publishing executive who financed a 
us expansion partly through highinterest junk bond credit and 
unsuccessfully launched a new st louis paper earlier this year 
relinquished control of his american newspaper interests to an 
investment partner em warburg pincus amp co 
in the same transaction ingersoll acquired warburgs 
halfinterest in a european newspaper publisher he thereby 
extricated himself from the debt burden of his three us 
publishing companies which owe about 700 million 
ingersoll said his primary motive was to exploit what he 
believed to be a vibrant market for newspapers in europe which has 
become the most economically dynamic part of the world 
but industry analysts said the high debt load ingersoll amassed 
in this country clearly was a key reason for the move which seemed 
to shatter his desire to become one of the biggest newspaper owners 
in the united states he had controlled 10 dailies and more than 
120 weeklies 
sheer size however does not necessarily make a newspaper 
empire invulnerable gannett the current no 1 newspaper company 
in the country disclosed its own form of financial distress this 
past week 
the 82daily newspaper giant which also publishes usa today 
nationally said it expected secondquarter earnings to fall that 
would mark the first time since gannett went public 22 years ago 
that quarterly earnings have declined from a year earlier the 
company is due to issue secondquarter earnings later this month 
as one of the most financially stable newspaper companies 
gannett does not have the debt problem ingersoll faced but both 
have been affected by what industry strategists have called some 
common underlying trends 
the newspaper industry has been suffering a slowdown for the 
last three years as advertising revenues have slowed said susan 
putnam who follows the newspaper business for moran amp associates 
inc an investment firm in greenwich conn theyve cut costs 
and got operations down to a lean level but revenue growth hasnt 
picked up so theyre suffering earnings declines 
the sluggishness rippling through the economy has complicated 
the outlook for newspapers which generally derive most of their 
revenue from retail automobile and classified advertising 
many retailers hurt by high debt levels of their own have cut 
back drastically on ads although publicizing sales in newspapers 
historically has been considered the cheapest and most effective 
way to attract customers 
automakers which also are slumping havent been aggressively 
offering rebates this year which in turn tends to reduce the 
amount of newspaper advertising by dealers 
within the classified ad category the most prevalent ads real 
estate and employment also have fallen analysts say 
in some economically depressed parts of the country where many 
properties are for sale for example owners and brokers simply 
have given up advertising in newspapers because of poor response 
this past week the conference board a new yorkbased business 
research group that tracks the volume of employment advertising 
said its helpwanted index dropped in may to the lowest level in 
four years in recessionbattered new england the level was off by 
nearly a third from a year earlier 
many newspapers have responded to their slump partly by 
aggressive drives to increase circulation this gives newspapers 
the justification to charge more for ads because presumably they 
are seen by more readers 
but this strategy has been been undermined by another problem 
that the newspaper industry increasingly is confronting many 
people particularly the young arent reading the papers 
some studies show for example that only 30 percent of 
americans under age 35 read a paper regularly about half the 
percentage of two decades ago 
perhaps the most troubling study was released recently by the 
times mirror center for the people amp the press which shows the 
younger generation knows less cares less and reads newspapers 
less than any generation in the past 50 years 
in other business and economic news this past week 
more evidence emerged of softness in the economy the 
unemployment rate fell slightly to 52 percent but that was due to 
fewer people looking for work new job growth remained weak 
